Comparing different conditions with scRNA-seq

Description

Its becoming more common that people are interested in performing experiments containing multiple experimental conditions. Handling this can be tricky. Well talk about data integration and differential expression between experimental conditions here.

Quick exploration

DimPlot(seurat, label=T)

DimPlot(seurat, group.by="seurat_annotations")

Whoa, there are two clusters of every cell type. Cool, right?!

Not really.

DimPlot(seurat, group.by="stim")

So how do we test the effects of stimulation on cell types? Some clusters contain both conditions (cluster 4 = NK & CD8 T), while others span multiple clusters (Cluster 0 & 3 = CD4 Naive T).

Integration

The goal of integration is to find an embedding that aligns samples by a specific experimental or technical variable, negating its effects on the embedding. There are multiple methods for doing this, but here well stay in the Seurat echo system and use their approach.

ifnb.list <- SplitObject(ifnb, split.by = "stim")

ifnb.list <- lapply(ifnb.list, FUN = function(x) {
    x <- NormalizeData(x)
    x <- FindVariableFeatures(x, selection.method = "vst", nfeatures = 2000)
})

features <- SelectIntegrationFeatures(object.list = ifnb.list)
immune.anchors <- FindIntegrationAnchors(object.list = ifnb.list, 
                                         anchor.features = features)
## Scaling features for provided objects
## Finding all pairwise anchors
## Running CCA
## Merging objects
## Finding neighborhoods
## Finding anchors
##  Found 16393 anchors
## Filtering anchors
##  Retained 6756 anchors
seurat <- IntegrateData(anchorset = immune.anchors)
## Merging dataset 1 into 2

Notice that we have a new activate assay in our Seurat object: integrated This contains aligned expression values that allow us to re-run the normal pipeline and get an integrated embedding:

seurat <- ScaleData(seurat)

Now our clusters correspond to individual cell types and are not separated by experimental condition. This is great because now we can take each cluster and do differential expression between conditions and this will tell us how each cell type is affected by stimulation. Well get to that in a second.

Integration is great to define unified clusters that arent driven by experimental/technical variables. If this variable is an uninteresting technical feature (eg. batch effect), we can just continue with using this UMAP. But often in papers, we want unified clusters, but want out UMAPs to still show the effect of our experimental condition. To do this, you can switch back to the RNA assay (unintegrated data), and re-run PCA and UMAP but skip the clustering:

DefaultAssay(seurat) <- "RNA"
seurat <- FindVariableFeatures(seurat)
seurat <- ScaleData(seurat)
## Centering and scaling data matrix
seurat <- RunPCA(seurat, verbose=F)
seurat <- RunUMAP(seurat, dims=1:30)
## 20:40:54 UMAP embedding parameters a = 0.9922 b = 1.112

And weve maintained the unified clusters.

Differential expression between conditions

IMPORTANT: A common mistake people make is that they integrate the data, but then keep using the integrated assays expression values. These values have been transformed to eliminate the variable youve integrated on. They are important for integration itself, but no longer reflect expression values and also contain dependencies that violate common statistics.

Even if you are using integrated data, you should use the RNA assay to look at gene expression and perform differential expression

I already switch back to the RNA assay in the last section, but I will do it again to emphasize my point

DefaultAssay(seurat) <- "RNA"
seurat #print out the seurat object to confirm you are using the right assay
## An object of class Seurat 
## 16053 features across 13999 samples within 2 assays 
## Active assay: RNA (14053 features, 2000 variable features)
##  1 other assay present: integrated
##  2 dimensional reductions calculated: pca, umap

With n=1 for the conditions, you are a little limited to what types of tests you can do, but the most common approach is likely to use a Wilcoxon test between conditions, treating each cell as an individual measurement. If you have replicates for conditions, best practice is probably to perform differential expression using standard bulk RNA-seq methods on pseudobulk data (ie. summing up all gene counts across cells of a replicate in a specific cluster). Check out the R package muscat for this. It performs pseudobulking and implements a variety of standard methods (DESeq, edgeR, etc).

Lets just proceed with our n=1. Seurats FindMarkers() function can perform the Wilcoxon test for us. Ill just perform differential expression for a single cell type / cluster (CD14 monocytes; cluster 0) here, but Ill include a function below that will iterate through this for all clusters

mono_dge <- FindMarkers(seurat, ident.1="STIM", ident.2="CTRL",
                        group.by="stim", #the metadata column that has experimental condition
                        subset.ident = 0, #what cluster to subset and run this on
                        logfc.threshold = 0.25, only.pos=F)

Heres a chunk of code if you want to run this differential expression across all clusters. Well skip it for now
